    "Warren W. Wiersbe": "Why is this just one short step from idolatry to immorality?\nv. 5), and Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` believed God\u2019s promise. The Hebrew word translated believed means \u201cto say amen.\u201d God gave a promise, and Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` responded with \u201cAmen!\u201d It was this faith that was counted for righteousness. The word counted in Romans 4:3 is a Greek word that means \u201cto put to one\u2019s account.\u201d It is a banking term. This same word is used eleven times in this chapter, translated \u201creckoned\u201d (Rom. 4:4, 9\u201310) and \u201cimputed\u201d (Rom. 4:6, 8, 11, 22\u201324), as well as \u201ccounted.\u201d When a man works, he earns a salary and this money is put to his account. But Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` did not work for his salvation; he simply trusted God\u2019s Word. It was Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ who did the work on the cross, and His righteousness was put on Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`\u2019s account. Romans 4:5 makes a startling statement: God justifies the ungodly! The law said, \u201cI will not justify the wicked\u201d (Ex. 23:7). The Old Testament judge was commanded to \u201cjustify the righteous, and condemn the wicked\u201d (Deut. 25:1). When Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` dedicated the temple, he asked God to condemn the wicked and justify the righteous (1 Kings 8:32). But God justifies the ungodly\u2014because there are no godly for Him to justify! He put our sins on Christ\u2019s account that He might put Christ\u2019s righteousness on our account. In Romans 4:6\u20138, Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` used David `[char_David_Rut_4]` as a witness, quoting from one of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s psalms of confession after his terrible sin with Bathsheba (Ps. 32:1\u20132). David `[char_David_Rut_4]` made two amazing statements: (1) God forgives sins and imputes righteousness apart from works; (2) God does not impute our sins. In other words, once we are justified, our record contains Christ\u2019s perfect righteousness and can never again contain our sins. Christians do sin, and these sins need to be forgiven if we are to have fellowship with God (1 John `[char_John_Ref]` 1:5\u20137), but these sins are not held against us. God does keep a record of our good works, so that He might reward us when Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` comes, but He is not keeping a record of our sins. (2) He was justified by grace, not law (vv. 9\u201317). As we have seen, the Jews gloried in circumcision and the law. If a Jew was to become righteous before God, he would have to be circumcised and obey the law. Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` had already made it clear in Romans 2:12\u201329 that there must be an inward obedience to the law, and a \u201ccircumcision of the heart.\u201d Mere external observances can never save the lost sinner. But Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` was declared righteous when he was in the state of uncircumcision. From the Jewish point of view, Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` was a Gentile. Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` was ninety-nine years old when he was circumcised (Gen. 17:23\u201327). This was more than fourteen years after the events in Genesis\n5. What was the purpose of animal sacrifices in the Old Testament? Why do we no longer need them?\n5. How are we justified? What is stated in Romans 5:1\u201321? What does justification mean to you?\n5. What should be the believer\u2019s relationship to sin? What does this look like in your own life?\n5. Why do you think Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]` may have used the commandment \u201cyou shall not covet\u201d as an example of lawbreaking? What are some laws you struggle with personally?\nv. 5). The unsaved person does not have the Spirit of God (Rom. 8:9) and lives in the flesh and for the flesh. His mind is centered on the things that satisfy the flesh. But the Christian has the Spirit of God within and lives in an entirely new and different sphere. His mind is fixed on the things of the Spirit. This does not mean that the unsaved person never does anything good, or that the believer never does anything bad. It means that the bent of their lives is different. One lives for the flesh, the other lives for the Spirit. Death\u2014life (\n5. What are the four contrasts mentioned concerning freedom from defeat?\n5. How does Israel\u2019s past history magnify the attributes of God?"
