    "Thomas Manton": "Crosses seldom come singly. Once God begins to test, he uses various methods of trial; and there is good reason for this. Different diseases must have different remedies. Pride, envy, covetousness, worldliness, wantonness, ambition are not all cured by the same remedy. One affliction pricks the bladder of pride, while another checks our desires. Do not murmur, then, if miseries come upon you like waves. Job\u2019s messengers came thick and fast one after another, telling of oxen, house, camels, sons, daughters, and all destroyed (see Job 1); messenger upon messenger, each with a sadder story. We have \u201call kinds of passions\u201d (Titus 3:3), and therefore have many kinds of trials. In Revelation 6 one horse comes after another\u2014the white, the red, the black, the pale. Once the floodgates are opened, several judgments follow in succession (see also Matthew 24:7). Learn also that God has several types of trial\u2014confiscation, banishment, poverty, infamy, reproach; some trials test us more than others. We must leave it to his wisdom to make the choice. Note 6 . Trials . James does not call them afflictions or persecutions but trials , because of God\u2019s purpose in sending them. The same word is used in 2 Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` 2:9\u2014\u201cThe Lord knows how to rescue godly men from trials.\u201d The afflictions of the saints are not judgments but corrections or trials\u2014God\u2019s discipline to mortify sin, or his means to discover grace, to prove our faith, love, patience, sincerity, constancy, etc. Watch over yourselves with great care so that no impatience, vanity, murmuring, or worldliness of spirit may appear in you. [v_1Th_4_13] An Exposition of the Epistle of James Commentary on\n28. Crosses seldom come singly. Once God begins to test, he uses various methods of trial; and there is good reason for this. Different diseases must have different remedies. Pride, envy, covetousness, worldliness, wantonness, ambition are not all cured by the same remedy. One affliction pricks the bladder of pride, while another checks our desires. Do not murmur, then, if miseries come upon you like waves. Job\u2019s messengers came thick and fast one after another, telling of oxen, house, camels, sons, daughters, and all destroyed (see Job 1); messenger upon messenger, each with [v_Tit_3_3] a sadder story. We have \u201call kinds of passions\u201d (Titus 3:3), and therefore have many kinds of trials. In Revelation 6 one horse comes after another\u2014the white, the red, the black, the pale. Once the floodgates are opened, several judgments follow in succession [v_Mat_24_7] (see also Matthew 24:7). Learn also that God has several types of trial\u2014confiscation, banishment, poverty, infamy, reproach; some trials test us more than others. We must leave it to his wisdom to make the choice. Note",
    "Unknown": "In such plenty as the necessities of the earth require; which also is a wonderful work of God.\nVer.",
    "A New and Concise Bible Dictionary": "Identified with the ford Abarah, . Most Editors of the Greek Testament read BETHANY. Bethanath. [Beth'-anath] City of Naphtali, the inhabitants of which were not driven out, but were made tributary. Joshua 19: 38; Judges 1:",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "The children of Dishon are these, etc.] The last of the seven sons of Seir, and who had two sons, Uz and Aran; from the former of these the land of Uz, inhabited by the [v_Lam_4_21] Edomites, had its name, (<250421>Lamentations 4:21); some have taken this to [v_Job_1_1] be the country of Job, (<180101>Job 1:1).\nVer.",
    "Commentary Vol. 90": "The centre of gravity, even in the Mosaic system, lay in the ethical and not in the ceremonial, and still more is that the case with Christianity; but even apparently slight matters of external observance, if divinely enjoined, should by no means be neglected. Origen applies this to persons who neglect wholesome instruction, and care only for rhetorical ornament; compare 1 Corinthians 1:\n28. Rochefoucauld: \"Hypocrisy is a sort of homage that vice pays to virtue.\" Pollok: \"He was a man who stole the livery of the court of heaven to serve the devil in.\" Matthew 23:30 f. It is very easy to condemn severely the misconduct of others, while secretly guilty of essential y the same sin. But \"God is not mocked,\" Galatians 6:\n28. One Great Sign At Jerusalem; also in Mark 13:14-23, Luke 21:20-\n28. Compare Luke 17:37, and the same image in Job 39:\n28. Immediately . The phrase is not exactly 'immediately after'; the adverb 'immediately' is connected with 'the sun shal be darkened,' etc. The substantial sense is however the same. So far as this passage relates to the destruction of Jerusalem, we may suppose that the events it indicates were to fol ow immediately after those predicted in 15-\n28. As regards the ulterior reference to the final parousia , there may prove to be in like manner some close consecution, but only the fulfilment is likely to show. After the tribulation of those days, viz, the tribulation attending upon the destruction of Jerusalem, see especial y Luke 21:",
    "Commentary Vol. 91": "The centre of gravity, even in the Mosaic system, lay in the ethical and not in the ceremonial, and still more is that the case with Christianity; but even apparently slight matters of external observance, if divinely enjoined, should by no means be neglected. Origen applies this to persons who neglect wholesome instruction, and care only for rhetorical ornament; compare 1 Corinthians 1:17. [v_Mat_23_24] Matthew 23:\n28. Rochefoucauld: \"Hypocrisy is a sort of homage that vice pays to virtue.\" Pollok: \"He was a man who stole the livery of the court of heaven to serve the devil in.\" [v_Mat_23_30] Matthew 23:30 f. It is very easy to condemn severely the misconduct of others, while secretly guilty [v_Gal_6_7] of essentially the same sin. But \"God is not mocked,\" Galatians 6:\n28. One Great Sign At Jerusalem; [v_Mrk_13_14] [v_Mrk_13_15] [v_Mrk_13_16] [v_Mrk_13_17] [v_Mrk_13_18] [v_Mrk_13_19] [v_Mrk_13_20] [v_Mrk_13_21] [v_Mrk_13_22] [v_Mrk_13_23] also in Mark 13:14-23, Luke 21:20-\n28. Compare Luke 17:37, and the same image in Job 39:\n28. Immediately. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` phrase is not exactly 'immediately after'; the adverb 'immediately' is connected with 'the sun shall be darkened,' etc. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` substantial sense is however the same. So far as this passage relates to the destruction of Jerusalem, we may suppose that the events it indicates were to follow immediately after those predicted in 15-\n28. As regards the ulterior reference to the final parousia, there may prove to be in like manner some close consecution, but only the fulfilment is likely to show. After the tribulation of those days, viz, the tribulation attending upon the [v_Luk_21_21] destruction of Jerusalem, see especially Luke 21:"
